 {"id":"flywheel_connectors-jdaro","title":"[REVIEW R2][HIGH] fcp-host: public cancel routes let any caller cancel tracked operations by guessed request ID","description":"Evidence:
- crates/fcp-host/src/bin/fcp-host.rs:2693-2695 exposes /rpc/cancel and /rpc/operations/cancel on the public router, outside the admin-auth protected route set.
- crates/fcp-host/src/bin/fcp-host.rs:4208-4226 handles cancellation with only Json<CancellationRequest>; there is no bearer, zone, principal, approval, or capability verification before state.cancellation.cancel(...).
- crates/fcp-host/src/bin/fcp-host.rs:4269 and 4303 track the caller-supplied InvokeRequest.id as the cancellation key, so a second caller that knows or predicts that request ID can target another in-flight operation.
- crates/fcp-host/tests/host_connector_integration.rs:3347-3353 and 3445-3451 exercise successful cancel requests with no auth material at all, which matches the live exposure.

Impact:
- Cross-principal denial of service against in-flight operations. Request IDs are client-controlled rather than host-issued secrets, so this is not mitigated by route obscurity.

Suggested fix outline:
1. Bind cancellation to the same authenticated principal/capability context as invoke, or move cancel under an authenticated route contract.
